<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="781" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="781">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="781">
Thoracic part narrower than cephalic part in dorsal view, distinctly concave posteriorly in lateral view (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 6" captionStartId="F6" captionText="Figure 6. Holotype of Sympolymnia lucasi (Taczanowski, 1871): A. Habitus dorsal and lateral views; B. Spermatheca and copulatory duct; C. Data label." figureDoi="10.3897/zse.96.55210.figure6" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/477343" pageId="0" pageNumber="781">6A</figureCitation>
); abdomen at most with slight dorsal constriction; bulb of male palp about 65% of cymbium length, tibial apophysis in retro-lateral view with relatively broad base (see 
<bibRefCitation author="Galiano, ME" journalOrPublisher="Museo Argentino de Ciencias Naturales Bernardino Rivadavia" pageId="0" pageNumber="781" pagination="339 - 380" refId="B13" refString="Galiano, ME, 1966. Salticidae (Araneae) formiciformes V. Revision del genero Synemosyna Hentz, 1846. Museo Argentino de Ciencias Naturales Bernardino Rivadavia 1: 339 - 380" title="Salticidae (Araneae) formiciformes V. Revision del genero Synemosyna Hentz, 1846." volume="1" year="1966">Galiano 1966</bibRefCitation>
for line drawings), apex with spine-like process; epigyne opening small (width: ~ 0.07 mm), transversely elliptical.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="781" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="781">
Geographical and ecological distribution (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 7" captionStartId="F7" captionText="Figure 7. Ecoregion distribution: &quot; Sympolymnia lucasi (Taczanowski, 1871); 3 / 4 S. cutleri sp. nov.; · S. shinahota sp. nov.; l S. lauretta (Peckham &amp; Peckham, 1892)." figureDoi="10.3897/zse.96.55210.figure7" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/477344" pageId="0" pageNumber="781">7</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="781">
The species was reported from Brazil (
<bibRefCitation author="Galiano, ME" journalOrPublisher="Revista de la Sociedad Argentina de Ciencias Naturales" pageId="0" pageNumber="781" pagination="27 - 39" refId="B14" refString="Galiano, ME, 1967. Salticidae (Araneae) formiciformes. VIII. Nuevas descripciones. Physis. Revista de la Sociedad Argentina de Ciencias Naturales 27: 27 - 39" title="Salticidae (Araneae) formiciformes. VIII. Nuevas descripciones. Physis." volume="27" year="1967">Galiano 1967</bibRefCitation>
) (the type location 
<normalizedToken originalValue="“Wassa”">&quot;Wassa&quot;</normalizedToken>
reported by 
<bibRefCitation author="Taczanowski, L" journalOrPublisher="Horae Societatis entomologicae Rossicae" pageId="0" pageNumber="781" pagination="32 - 132" refId="B50" refString="Taczanowski, L, 1871. Les araneides de la Guyane francaise. Horae Societatis entomologicae Rossicae 8: 32 - 132" title="Les araneides de la Guyane francaise." volume="8" year="1871">Taczanowski [1871]</bibRefCitation>
refers to the river or the area of 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Uaçá">Uaca</normalizedToken>
, which was formerly situated in French Guiana, now Brazil), French Guiana (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1186/2193-1801-2-361" author="Vedel, V" journalOrPublisher="SpringerPlus" pageId="0" pageNumber="781" pagination="1 - 19" refId="B51" refString="Vedel, V, Rheims, CA, Murienne, J, Brescovit, AD, 2013. Biodiversity baseline of the French Guiana spider fauna. SpringerPlus 2: 1 - 19, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1186/2193-1801-2-361" title="Biodiversity baseline of the French Guiana spider fauna." url="https://doi.org/10.1186/2193-1801-2-361" volume="2" year="2013">Vedel et al. 2013</bibRefCitation>
), Colombia (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1080/01650529109360850" author="Cutler, B" journalOrPublisher="Studies on Neotropical Fauna and Environment" pageId="0" pageNumber="781" pagination="171 - 177" refId="B9" refString="Cutler, B, Mueller, HG, 1991. The spider genus Synemosyna in northern Colombia (Araneae: Salticidae). Studies on Neotropical Fauna and Environment 26: 171 - 177, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1080/01650529109360850" title="The spider genus Synemosyna in northern Colombia (Araneae: Salticidae)." url="https://doi.org/10.1080/01650529109360850" volume="26" year="1991">
Cutler and 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Müller">Mueller</normalizedToken>
1991
</bibRefCitation>
) and Peru (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1080/01650528509360674" author="Cutler, B" journalOrPublisher="Studies on Neotropical Fauna and Environment" pageId="0" pageNumber="781" pagination="83 - 91" refId="B6" refString="Cutler, B, 1985. Taxonomic notes on Neotropical species in the genus Synemosyna (Araneae: Salticidae). Studies on Neotropical Fauna and Environment 20: 83 - 91, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1080/01650528509360674" title="Taxonomic notes on Neotropical species in the genus Synemosyna (Araneae: Salticidae)." url="https://doi.org/10.1080/01650528509360674" volume="20" year="1985">Cutler 1985</bibRefCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Taczanowski" baseAuthorityYear="1871" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Synemosyna" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Synemosyna lucasi" order="Araneae" pageId="0" pageNumber="781" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lucasi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="781">Synemosyna lucasi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
appears to be associated with semi-deciduous or deciduous forests (Guajira-Barranquilla Xeric shrub, 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Sinú">Sinu</normalizedToken>
Valley dry forest) and moist Amazon forests (Tocantins 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Pindaré">Pindare</normalizedToken>
moist forests, 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Marajó">Marajo</normalizedToken>
<normalizedToken originalValue="várzea">varzea</normalizedToken>
and Ucayali moist forests). 
<bibRefCitation author="Cutler, B" journalOrPublisher="Journal of the Trinidad and Tobago Field Naturalists' Club" pageId="0" pageNumber="781" pagination="39 - 44" refId="B8" refString="Cutler, B, Edwards, GB, 2002. The Jumping Spiders (Araneae: Salticidae) of Trinidad and Tobago. Living World. Journal of the Trinidad and Tobago Field Naturalists' Club 2002: 39 - 44" title="The Jumping Spiders (Araneae: Salticidae) of Trinidad and Tobago. Living World." volume="2002" year="2002">Cutler and Edwards (2002)</bibRefCitation>
recorded 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. lucasi" pageId="0" pageNumber="781" rank="species" species="lucasi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="781">S. cf. lucasi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from Trinidad Island (Lesser Antilles). The taxonomic status of these specimens remains to be determined. 
<taxonomicName authority="Perger &amp; Rubio, 2020" authorityName="Perger &amp; Rubio" authorityYear="2020" baseAuthorityName="Taczanowski" baseAuthorityYear="1871" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Sympolymnia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Sympolymnia lucasi" order="Araneae" pageId="0" pageNumber="781" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lucasi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="781">Sympolymnia lucasi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was not observed in the present study area and there is no confirmed record of this species for Bolivia.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
